{"title_page": "Battle of Dry Wood Creek", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Battle of Dry Wood Creek<br>{{small|Action at Dry Wood Creek}}\n| partof      = the [[Trans-Mississippi Theater of the American Civil War|Trans-Mississippi Theater]] of the [[American Civil War]]\n| image      = {{Location map |USA Missouri}}\n| caption    =\n| date        = {{Start date|1861|9|2}}\n| place       = [[Vernon County, Missouri]]\n| coordinates = <!--{{Coord|37|50|20|N|94|30|25|W}}-->\n| map type    = Missouri\n| result      = [[Confederate government of Missouri|Confederate]] victory\n| combatant1  = {{Nowrap|[[File:Flag of the Missouri State Guard.svg|Missouri|border|23px]] [[Confederate government of Missouri|Missouri (Confederate)]]}}\n| combatant2  = {{flagicon|USA|1861}} [[United States]] ([[Union (American Civil War)|Union]])\n| commander1  = [[File:Flag of the Missouri State Guard.svg|Missouri|border|23px]] [[Sterling Price]] <br />\n| commander2  = {{flagicon|United States|1861}} Brig. Gen. [[James H. Lane (Senator)|James H. Lane]]\n| units1      = [[Missouri State Guard]]\n| units2      = Lane's Kansas Brigade\n| strength1   = 6,000{{endash}}10,000\n| strength2   = 600{{endash}}1,200\n| casualties1 = 25 total <br/> 2 killed <br/> 23 wounded\n| casualties2 = 11 total <br/> 5 killed <br/> 6 wounded\n| campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Operations to Control Missouri}}\n}}\nThe '''Battle of Dry Wood Creek''' (also known as the '''Battle of the Mules''') was fought on September 2, 1861 in [[Vernon County, Missouri]] during the [[American Civil War]].  After his victory at the [[Battle of Wilson's Creek]], [[Sterling Price]] and the [[Missouri State Guard]] moved further north into [[Missouri]].  A force of [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] troops under [[James H. Lane (Senator)|James H. Lane]] moved from [[Fort Scott, Kansas]] to attempt to intercept Price's army, and set an ambush along [[Dry Wood Creek]] in Vernon County.  Price's Missouri State Guard troops outnumbered Lane's [[Kansas]] troops, and forced Lane to retreat to Fort Scott after a two hour skirmish.  In their retreat, Lane's troops abandoned their supplies and mules to the Missourians. Price followed up his victory by continuing his northward march, culminating in the [[Siege of Lexington]].\n\n==Background==\n{{See also|Missouri in the American Civil War}}\n\nAfter the outbreak of the [[American Civil War]] in 1861, [[Missouri]] was considered to be a [[Border states (American Civil War)|border state]], as it was a [[Slavery in the United States|slavery was legal]] within the state, but it did not vote to [[Secession in the United States|secede]].  [[Governor of Missouri]] [[Claiborne F. Jackson]] supported the [[Confederate States of America]], and began to use [[militia]] to support the Confederate cause in Missouri by marching towards the [[arsenal]] in [[St. Louis, Missouri|St. Louis]].  [[Brigadier General (United States)|Brigadier General]] [[Nathaniel Lyon]], commander of the Union forces in St. Louis, acted quickly by forcing Jackson's militia to surrender in the [[Camp Jackson affair]].  After the debacle at Camp Jackson, Jackson formed a new organization named the [[Missouri State Guard]] and appointed [[Sterling Price]] to command it.  Lyon moved to confront Price's new force, defeating it at the [[Battle of Boonville]].  Price and the Missouri State Guard retreated to the vicinity of [[Springfield, Missouri|Springfield]] in southwestern Missouri, where it was joined by a [[Confederate States Army]] force commanded by Brigadier General [[Benjamin McCulloch]].  On August 10, Lyon decided to attack the combined forces of Price and McCulloch while they were encamped along [[Wilsons Creek, Missouri|Wilsons Creek]], despite being outnumbered by the Confederates and Missourians by a factor of over two-to-one.  In the ensuing [[Battle of Wilson's Creek]], the Union forces were defeated and Lyon killed.{{sfn|Kennedy|1998|pp=19{{endash}}23}}\n\nAfter Wilson's Creek, the Union army retreated to [[Rolla, Missouri]].  McCulloch and his forces withdrew to [[Arkansas]], and Price's Missouri State Guard occupied Springfield.{{sfn|Monaghan|1984|p=182}}  [[John C. Fremont]] arrived to take control of Union forces in the state, and [[James H. Lane (Senator)|James H. Lane]] took command of several [[Kansas]] regiments stationed at [[Fort Scott, Kansas|Fort Scott]].  Meanwhile, Price began to advance north with a force estimated to number at either 6,000<ref name=\"ohio state\">{{cite web |title=Dry Wood Creek (Big Dry Wood Creek, Battle of the Mules) |url=https://ehistory.osu.edu/battles/dry-wood-creek-big-dry-wood-creek-battle-mules |website=ehistory.osu |publisher=Ohio State University |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref> or 10,000 men.{{sfn|Monaghan|1984|p=184}}  In response to Price's incursion, Fremont declared Missouri to be subject to [[martial law]].{{sfn|Monaghan|1984|pp=182\u2013185}}\n\n==Battle==\n[[File:Dry Wood Creek Battlefield Missouri.jpg|thumb|300px|alt=Map of Dry Wood Creek Battlefield core and study areas by the American Battlefield Protection Program|Dry Wood Creek battlefield]]\n\nLane sent his forces, estimated to number either 600<ref name=\"ohio state\" /> or 1,200 men, out to intercept Price's army, and set an ambush along [[Dry Wood Creek]] in [[Vernon County, Missouri]] on September 2.{{sfn|Gerteis|2012|p=99}}  The area around Dry Wood Creek was wooded, giving Lane the element of surprise.  The leading portions of the Missouri State Guard fell into Lane's trap.  Price then brought up more troops, and the Missourians' numerical advantage was a deciding factor in the engagement.  Lane's [[skirmishers]] were driven back from an advanced position, and the main Union force used the covers of the woods to hold of Price for about two hours.  However, Price's men eventually overwhelmed the Kansans, and Lane's troops retreated to Fort Scott.  During the retreat, Lane's men abandoned their supplies and mules to the Missouri State Guard.  Price stated that an important factor in the victory was the fighting experience the Missouri State Guard had gained at Wilson's Creek.{{sfn|Gerteis|2012|pp=99\u2013100}}  The capture of the mules led the battle to be sometimes known as the \"Battle of the Mules\".<ref name=\"ohio state\" /> After defeating Lane, Price's army then headed north to [[Johnson County, Missouri]].{{sfn|Gerteis|2012|p=100}}\n\nIn a report filed after the battle, Lane states that his forces lost five men killed and six wounded.<ref name=\"lane battle report\">{{cite web |last1=Lane |first1=James H. |title=Action at Dry Wood Creek |url=https://ehistory.osu.edu/books/official-records/003/0163 |website=ehistory.osu.edu |publisher=Ohio State University |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>  In his post-action report, Price estimated his loss to be two men killed and twenty-three wounded, although he noted that most of the wounds were not serious.<ref name=\"official records\">{{cite web |title=The War of the Rebellion: A Compilation of the Official Records of the Union and Confederate Armies: Series 1, Volume 53 |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=coo.31924080779543&view=1up&seq=443 |website=babel.hathitrust.org |publisher=United States War Department |accessdate=16 March 2020 |pages=435{{endash}}436}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath and legacy==\nAfter reaching Johnson County, Price continued to [[Lexington, Missouri]], where a Union garrison was defending the town.  Price's men surrounded the garrison, initiating the [[Siege of Lexington]].  The Missouri State Guard subdued the Union garrison, at one point using [[hemp]] bales as cover while attacking uphill.  After forcing the Union garrison to surrender, the Missouri State Guard remained in the Lexington area for two weeks before Price ordered the unit to return south.{{sfn|Monaghan|1984|pp=185\u2013194}}  The victory at Dry Wood Creek had allowed Price to be able to continue his northward expedition.{{sfn|Castel|1968|p=50}}\n\nToday, the site of the battle is commemorated with a series of markers near [[Deerfield, Missouri]].  A museum in nearby [[Nevada, Missouri]] provides coverage of both the Battle of Dry Wood Creek and the American Civil War in Missouri as a whole.{{sfn|Weeks|2009|p=42}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book |last=Castel |first=Albert |title=General Sterling Price and the Civil War in the West |date=1968 |publisher=Louisiana State University Press |location=Baton Rouge, Louisiana |isbn=0-8071-1854-0 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Gerteis |first1=Louis S. |title=The Civil War in Missouri |date=2012 |publisher=University of Missouri Press |location=Columbia, Missouri |isbn=978-0-8262-1972-5 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Kennedy |first=Frances |title=The Civil War Battlefield Guide |date=1998 |edition=2nd |publisher=Houghton Mifflin |location=Boston/New York |isbn=978-0-395-74012-5|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Monaghan |first1=Jay |title=Civil War on the Western Border, 1854{{endash}}1865 |date=1984 |publisher=University of Nebraska Press |location=Lincoln, Nebraska |isbn=978-0-8032-8126-4 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Weeks |first1=Michael |title=The Complete Civil War Road Trip Guide |date=2009 |publisher=The Countryman Press |location=Woodstock, Vermont |isbn=978-0-88150-860-4 |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041119074750/http://www.griffingweb.com/captain_creitz%27s_diary.htm Diary of a Union cavalryman present at Dry Wood Creek]\n\n{{Missouri in the Civil War}}\n\n{{Coord|37.8197|-94.4862|display=title|region:US-MO_type:event}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dry Wood Creek}}\n[[Category:Operations to Control Missouri|Dry Wood Creek]]\n[[Category:Battles of the Trans-Mississippi Theater of the American Civil War|Dry Wood Creek]]\n[[Category:Confederate victories of the American Civil War|Dry Wood Creek]]\n[[Category:Battles of the American Civil War in Missouri|Dry Wood Creek]]\n[[Category:Vernon County, Missouri]]\n[[Category:1861 in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:1861 in Missouri]]\n[[Category:September 1861 events]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Battle of Dry Wood Creek<br>{{small|Action at Dry Wood Creek}}\n| partof      = the [[Trans-Mississippi Theater of the American Civil War|Trans-Mississippi Theater]] of the [[American Civil War]]\n| image      = {{Location map |USA Missouri}}\n| caption    =\n| date        = {{Start date|1861|9|2}}\n| place       = [[Vernon County, Missouri]]\n| coordinates = <!--{{Coord|37|50|20|N|94|30|25|W}}-->\n| map type    = Missouri\n| result      = [[Confederate government of Missouri|Confederate]] victory\n| combatant1  = {{Nowrap|[[File:Flag of the Missouri State Guard.svg|Missouri|border|23px]] [[Confederate government of Missouri|Missouri (Confederate)]]}}\n| combatant2  = {{flagicon|USA|1861}} [[United States]] ([[Union (American Civil War)|Union]])\n| commander1  = [[File:Flag of the Missouri State Guard.svg|Missouri|border|23px]] [[Sterling Price]] <br />\n| commander2  = {{flagicon|United States|1861}} Brig. Gen. [[James H. Lane (Senator)|James H. Lane]]\n| units1      = [[Missouri State Guard]]\n| units2      = Lane's Kansas Brigade\n| strength1   = 6,000{{endash}}10,000\n| strength2   = 600{{endash}}1,200\n| casualties1 = 25 total <br/> 2 killed <br/> 23 wounded\n| casualties2 = 11 total <br/> 5 killed <br/> 6 wounded\n| campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Operations to Control Missouri}}\n}}\nThe '''Battle of Dry Wood Creek''' (also known as the '''Battle of the Mules''') was fought on September 2, 1861 in [[Vernon County, Missouri]] during the [[American Civil War]].  After his victory at the [[Battle of Wilson's Creek]], [[Sterling Price]] and the [[Missouri State Guard]] moved further north into [[Missouri]].  A force of [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] troops under [[James H. Lane (Senator)|James H. Lane]] moved f